==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: itinerary
<hw>i*tin"er*a*ry</hw> <pr>(⟦isl⟧*t⟦icr⟧n"⟦etil⟧r*⟦asl⟧*r⟦ycr⟧)</pr>,
<pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>itinerarius</ets>: cf. F.
<ets>itin⟦eacute⟧raire</ets>. See <er>Itinerant</er>.]</ety>
<def>Itinerant; traveling; passing from place to place; done on a
journey.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It was rather an <qex>itinerary</qex> circuit of justice than a
progress.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Itinerary</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Itinerary
<hw>I*tin"er*a*ry</hw>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Itineraries</plw>
<pr>(⟦isl⟧*t⟦icr⟧n"⟦etil⟧r*⟦asl⟧*r⟦icr⟧z)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L.
<ets>itinerarium</ets>: cf. F. <ets>itin⟦eacute⟧raire</ets>. See
<er>Itinerary</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>An account of
travels, or a register of places and distances as a guide to travelers;
<as>as, the <ex>Itinerary</ex> of Antoninus</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A detailed plan for a journey, including a list of
places to be visited, and often other information such as the dates,
places of residence, and transportation to be used during the journey;
<as>as, the catacombs aren't on our <ex>itinerary</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>itinerate</ent>⟦br⟧
